@node The Common Lisp Object System
@section The Common Lisp Object System

This section is intended for readers unfamiliar with Common Lisp.  It is not a full treatment of
CLOS, the Common Lisp Object System, but should provide enough background that you can understand
the rest of this book.

CLOS is unusual, among object-oriented languages, in several ways:

@itemize
@item
Common Lisp was not designed from scratch as an object-oriented language; CLOS was added on to it
relatively late in its evolution.  There were other OO extensions to Lisp that preceded it and
influenced its design, notably Flavors on the MIT Lisp Machine and LOOPS in Xerox Interlisp-D.

@item
CLOS organizes functionality quite differently from most OO languages.  A class definition specifies
only the class's data: its superclasses and slots (fields).  It does not specify the methods on the
class.  Instead, @dfn{generic functions} abstract the notion of an operation that can be invoked on
different classes; each method is associated with a generic function.

Imagine a hierarchy of classes with methods in a mainstream OO language.  For each method, either it
overrides a method of the same name in a superclass, or it does not; the latter we call root
methods.  Consider a single root method and all the subclass methods that override it; that's the
set of methods that forms a generic function.
@item
CLOS supports multiple dispatch.  Each method on a generic function has a list of @dfn{specializers}
defining a list of parameter types on which the method is appiicable.  Invocation of a generic
function on a list of arguments (conceptually) scans the methods of the generic function, to find
the method whose specializers best match the types of the arguments, then dispatches to that method.
(A caching mechanism makes this much cheaper, in practice, than it sounds.)

The language spec has a detailed definition of what ``best match'' means here, but the short version
is that since there are subtyping relationships involved, we want a method whose specializers are
more specific to shadow one whose specializers are less specific, when the arguments are of the more
specific types.  In the single-dispatch case, this generates the familiar overriding behavior of
other OO languages: a method on a subclass overrides one of the same name on a superclass.
@item
The classes available to be specialized on are not limited to those the user has defined; CL defines
a hierarchy of built-in classes that can also be used.  The class named @code{t} is the top of the
hierarchy, the class of all objects.  When no specializer is explicitly given for a parameter of a
method, the specializer defaults to @code{t}.

CLOS also provides a way to specialize a method parameter on a symbol, so that the method will be
called only when that specific symbol is passed.  FSet uses this for its generic function
@href{Generic Function @code{convert}, @code{convert}}, to specify the intended conversion.
@end itemize

Here's the first line of a sample entry from the API Reference chapter:

@deffn Method {find-if (t set)} @ pred s @r{&key} key
@end deffn

Here @code{find-if} is the generic function, and @code{(t set)} is the list of specializers.  This
method will be invoked on a call whose second argument is a set.  The required parameters are
@var{pred} and @code{s}; @code{s} will be bound to the set.

For brevity, I have usually omitted trailing @code{t} specializers in this book, since they have no
effect on method selection.

Oh, maybe I should say a little about optional and keyword parameters.  CL has both of these, marked
in parameter lists by @code{&optional} and @code{&key} respectively.  Optional parameters match
arguments by position; for keyword parameters, the argument must be preceded by the parameter name
as a keyword symbol (@i{i.e.}, preceded by a colon).  Both optional and keyword parameters may be
given default values in the parameter list; the default default is @code{nil}.  Examples:

@example
(defun foo (x &optional y (z 0)) ...)
(defun bar (x &key y (z 3)) ...)
;;; some possible calls
(foo 17)             ; x = 17, y = nil, z = 0
(foo 17 42)          ; x = 17, y = 42, z = 0
(foo 17 42 19)       ; x = 17, y = 42, z = 19
(bar 22)             ; x = 22, y = nil, z = 3
(bar 22 :z 7)        ; x = 22, y = nil, z = 7
(bar 22 :z 7 :y 13)  ; x = 22, y = 13, z = 7
@end example

